  1. For color, different hues of the color represented the different variation in cty MPG. For shape, larger circles represented higher amounts of cty MPG vs smaller circles for lower cty MPG. However, shape was not able to be mapped, because there are a finite number of unique shapes, that wouldnt be able to map all the different values a contentious variable can take.
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = cty, color = cty, shape = class))
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values
## because more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have 7.
## Consider specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
## Warning: Removed 62 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  1. The graph above shows a mapping of cty MPG to two different aesthetics. You can see that the plot uses both color hues and circle sizes to show the changes in the cty MPG variable.
ggplot(mpg, aes(model, cty, fill = manufacturer)) +
  geom_point(stroke = 3)

  1. The stroke aesthetic is used to modify the width of the border of shapes that have them. This works with shape 21.
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = displ < 5))

  1. When you map an aesthetics to something other than a a variable name, such as a conditional statement, it evaluates each point against that statement and sets them accordingly. In the example above, all values of displ less than 5 were evaluated as True and colored teal, while at least 5 were with red.

Exercise 3.5.1

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, ncol = 2)

  1. Using faceting vs color allows for another degree of separation. This makes the relationships for each class vs the x & y a lot easier to see as they each have their own mini plot. The disadvantage here is that it is more difficult to see how all this data relates to one another, especially for plots with similar patterns such as compact and subcompact. If there were in the same plot, just colored different, the relationship would be a bit more obvious. For very larger data sets, it would probably be better to use faceting as having too many plots of different colors all on one plot would be too much clutter to process.
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

  1. Facet_wrap allows you to control the output display of the plots using ncols and nrows. They stand for number of columns and number of rows and control only the display output. Facet_grid doesnt have ncols or nrows because the number of columns and rows is determined by the variables passed into the facet_grid argument.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

  1. The above code is predicted to be a plot of displ vs hwy. Along with color coordination for drv. The plot will be a dot plot with a trend curve overlay on it.
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_smooth(
    mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv),
    show.legend = FALSE
  )
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

  1. show.legend = False controls if the plots legend will show or not. If we remove remove it or set it to True, well see the legend. I think it was used earlier in the chapter because multiple graphs were being compared to one another, in a situation like that, it is unnecessary to have multiple legends.

  2. The se agrument in geom_smooth is for displaying a confidence interval around the smooth line.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_smooth(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

  1. Will these two graphs look different? Why/why not?

No they are essentially the same thing. ggplot is essentiallys visul layers on top of the plot. Since the aes mapping is the samne for geom_point and geom_smooth, you only need to write the mapping once, and it can be done in the plot definition.

  1. Recreate the R code necessary to generate the following graphs.
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Section 3.7.1

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ)) +
  geom_bar()

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_col()

  1. Geom_bar takes in an x variabler and makes the heights of the bars equal to the counts. Geom_col takes in both an x & y, thus the heights of the bars represent values of the y variable.
